Speedeet and Wilar are two 12-year-old best friends from Pike Street, Kitty, Georgetown. Every week they have an adventure that teaches them something new about Guyana.
The Biggest Ship in the Sea The breeze was blowing strong off the Demerara River when Speedeet and Wilar parked their bicycles by the seawall and looked out at the brown water stretching toward the Atlantic.
&ldquo;You know what out deh?&rdquo; Speedeet said, pointing toward the horizon where the river met the ocean. &ldquo;Way, way, way out deh?&rdquo;
Wilar squinted. &ldquo;Water?&rdquo;
&ldquo;SHIPS, Wilar. Big big big ships. Bigger than anything you ever see.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Bigger than de ferry?&rdquo;
Speedeet laughed so hard he nearly fell off the seawall. &ldquo;Bai, de ferry could park INSIDE one of these ships and still have room fuh a cricket pitch. Dem call them FPSOs.&rdquo;
&ldquo;FP-what-now?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Floating Production, Storage, and Offloading vessels,&rdquo; Speedeet said, like he was reading from an encyclopedia. Which he had been. &ldquo;Dem sit in de ocean over de oil wells and pump de oil from under de seabed. Store it. Then load it onto tanker ships that carry it away.&rdquo;
Wilar thought about this. &ldquo;So de oil under WE water.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Correct.&rdquo;
&ldquo;And de ship pump it up.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Correct.&rdquo;
&ldquo;And now Exxon own ALL FOUR ships.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Also correct. Dey just buy de fourth one. US$2.3 billion dollars.&rdquo;
Wilar whistled. He didn&rsquo;t actually know how much $2.3 billion was, but he knew it was more than his mother spent on groceries. Significantly more.
They sat on the seawall, legs dangling, watching a fishing boat chug upriver. The fisherman waved. They waved back.
&ldquo;Speedeet,&rdquo; Wilar said, in the careful voice he used when he was thinking hard. &ldquo;If somebody come to YOUR yard, dig up YOUR mango tree, sell de mangoes, and then buy a truck with de mango money ‚Äî whose truck is it?&rdquo;
Speedeet looked at his friend. &ldquo;Dat is a very good question.&rdquo;
&ldquo;And if dey tell you, &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t worry, you getting some of de mango money back ‚Äî AFTER I pay fuh de truck, de gas, de driver, de insurance, and me lunch&rsquo; ‚Äî how much mango money you actually getting?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Less than you think.&rdquo;
&ldquo;EXACTLY.&rdquo;
They sat in silence for a while. A pelican dove into the water and came up with a fish. The pelican, Wilar noted, did not have to share the fish with anyone.
&ldquo;But here&rsquo;s de thing,&rdquo; Speedeet said eventually. &ldquo;Dem ships also creating jobs. Guyanese people working in de oil industry. Engineers, technicians, supply chain people. De money flowing into de economy in different ways ‚Äî not just de direct oil revenue.&rdquo;
&ldquo;So it&rsquo;s complicated.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Everything in Guyana complicated, Wilar. Dat&rsquo;s why we gotta read. And ask questions. And not just accept what ONE person or ONE newspaper tell we.&rdquo;
Wilar pulled a folded piece of newspaper from his back pocket. He always carried newspaper. His grandmother said it was good for wrapping fish, swatting flies, AND getting educated.
&ldquo;Look here,&rdquo; Wilar said, pointing to an article. &ldquo;Dem also putting $25 billion into green energy. Solar, hydro, gas-to-energy. So eventually, we might not need to depend on just oil.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Dat&rsquo;s smart,&rdquo; Speedeet said. &ldquo;Because oil don&rsquo;t last forever. Ask Trinidad.&rdquo;
&ldquo;True true.&rdquo;
They hopped off the seawall and picked up their bikes. The sun was getting hot and Speedeet&rsquo;s mother had promised cook-up rice for lunch, which was not the kind of promise you tested by being late.
As they pedalled back through Kitty, passing the familiar landmarks of Pike Street ‚Äî the rum shop, the parlour, Miss Devi&rsquo;s house with the big mango tree, the gutter that always overflow when rain fall ‚Äî Wilar had one more thought.
&ldquo;Speedeet.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yeah?&rdquo;
&ldquo;When we grow up, we should build we OWN ship.&rdquo;
Speedeet grinned. &ldquo;A Guyanese FPSO?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Why not? We smart. We read. We ask questions. And we know where de oil is.&rdquo;
Speedeet pedalled faster, the wind in his face, the future wide open like the Atlantic.
&ldquo;First,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;we gotta pass Mathematics.&rdquo;
&ldquo;DETAILS!&rdquo; Wilar shouted, and they raced home laughing.
LEARN SOMETHING NEW!
What is an FPSO? A Floating Production, Storage, and Offloading vessel is a giant ship that processes and stores oil pumped from beneath the ocean floor. Guyana has four FPSOs operating in the Stabroek Block, about 200 km offshore.
What is ringfencing? When an oil company operates multiple projects, ringfencing means each project&rsquo;s costs can only be recovered from THAT project&rsquo;s profits. Without it, costs from one project can reduce profits from another ‚Äî meaning less money for the country.
What is renewable energy? Energy from sources that naturally replenish ‚Äî like sunlight, wind, and water. Guyana is investing in hydropower and solar to reduce dependence on oil and imported fuel.
Speedeet and Wilar is a children&rsquo;s educational series set in Georgetown, Guyana. New stories every Sunday.

üçú DE CHINESE RESTAURANT ADVENTURE A Speedeet &amp; Wilar Story from Pike Street, Kitty
&ldquo;Speedeet! SPEEDEET!&rdquo;
Wilar come running down Pike Street like somebody chasing he with a cutlass. But he face wasn&rsquo;t scared ‚Äî he face was EXCITED.
&ldquo;Wha happen?&rdquo; Speedeet look up from de marble game he was winning against Little Sanjay.
&ldquo;Me uncle know de man who own de Chinese restaurant! De one next to Kitty Cinema church on Alexander Street!&rdquo;
Speedeet eyes get big. EVERYBODY know dat restaurant. De smell alone could make you forget you had lunch already.
&ldquo;So?&rdquo;
&ldquo;SO? He say he could carry we inside! INSIDE de kitchen!&rdquo;
Little Sanjay marble roll away forgotten. Speedeet was already on he feet.
&ldquo;Leh we go!&rdquo;
üö∂ DE WALK TO ALEXANDER STREET De two boys walk fast-fast down de road. Wilar uncle, Mr. Doodnauth, was waiting by de restaurant door looking important.
&ldquo;Alright boys, Mr. Chen say we could go in de back. But NO TOUCHING. You hear me? NO. TOUCHING.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yes Uncle,&rdquo; Wilar say, all innocent.
Speedeet just nod. He fingers already twitching.
Mr. Chen appear at de door ‚Äî a small man with a big smile and a apron that look like it see more battles than de Guyana Defence Force.
&ldquo;Ah! Doodnauth! Come, come! Bring de boys!&rdquo;
And just so, dey was IN.
üçó DE KITCHEN Speedeet thought he know what a kitchen look like. He mother kitchen had a stove, a pot, and sometimes a lizard on de wall.
DIS was something else.
Rows and ROWS of chicken hanging neat-neat on racks. Golden brown. Glistening. Looking like dey posing for a photograph.
&ldquo;Oh gosh&hellip;&rdquo; Speedeet whisper.
De SMELL hit he like a wave. Garlic. Ginger. Soy sauce. Something sweet. Something savory. All of it mixing together into one beautiful cloud dat wrap around he brain and squeeze.
&ldquo;You boys hungry?&rdquo; Mr. Chen ask, already knowing de answer.
Wilar nod so hard he glasses nearly fly off.
ü•° DE TASTING Mr. Chen start pulling out dish after dish.
Sweet and sour pork. Wilar couldn&rsquo;t eat dat, but Speedeet demolished it.
Chicken chow mein. Both boys attack it like dey never see food before.
Fried wontons. Gone in seconds.
And then&hellip;
Mr. Chen bring out a big plate of fried rice.
&ldquo;Dis,&rdquo; he say with pride, &ldquo;is me SPECIAL Chop Suey Fried Rice. Secret recipe.&rdquo;
Speedeet look at de rice. It had everything. Chicken pieces. Vegetables. Egg. Shrimp.
And something else.
Something&hellip; unfamiliar.
üëÄ DE DISCOVERY Speedeet was shoveling rice into he mouth when he fork hit something strange.
He look down.
He squint.
He lean closer.
&ldquo;Wilar&hellip;&rdquo;
&ldquo;Wha?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Wilar, look at dis.&rdquo;
Wilar push up he glasses and peer into Speedeet plate.
Sitting right there, mixed in with de rice and de vegetables and de regular chicken pieces&hellip;
Was a CHICKEN HEAD.
Complete with de little red comb on top.
&ldquo;OH GOSH!&rdquo; Wilar jump back like de head was gon bite he.
Speedeet just stare at it.
De chicken head stare back.
Well, not really. De eyes was closed. But it FELT like it was staring.
ü§î DE DECISION Mr. Doodnauth and Mr. Chen was deep in conversation by de freezer, not paying attention.
Wilar was backing away slow-slow. &ldquo;Speedeet, put it down. PUT IT DOWN.&rdquo;
But Speedeet mind was racing.
He had eat chicken leg before. Chicken wing. Chicken breast. Chicken back. He mother even make chicken foot soup one time.
But chicken HEAD?
Dis was new territory.
Dis was ADVENTURE.
&ldquo;Wilar,&rdquo; Speedeet say slowly, &ldquo;you ever eat chicken head before?&rdquo;
&ldquo;NO! And I not starting today!&rdquo;
Speedeet look at de head again. De little comb was actually kinda crispy looking. Like a tiny red chip.
He think about all de times he tell Wilar to be brave. All de times he say &ldquo;Nothing ventured, nothing gained.&rdquo; All de times he climb de mango tree first.
How he could call heself SPEEDEET ‚Äî de bravest boy on Pike Street ‚Äî if he scared of a little chicken head?
Besides, de comb was looking kinda interesting. Soft. Reddish. Like a little rubbery crown.
üòã DE MOMENT OF TRUTH Speedeet take a deep breath.
He pick up de chicken head with he fork.
Wilar cover he eyes. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t watch. I CAN&rsquo;T WATCH.&rdquo;
Speedeet open he mouth.
And he eat it.
&hellip;
&hellip;
&hellip;
&ldquo;Well?&rdquo; Wilar peek through he fingers.
Speedeet was chewing. Slow. Thoughtful. Like a food critic on TV.
He eyes get wide.
De comb wasn&rsquo;t crispy like he expected. It was SOFT. Chewy. Like nothing he ever taste before. It had dis unusual texture dat bounce around in he mouth ‚Äî rubbery but in a GOOD way. He chew on it delightfully, exploring every bit of de strange new sensation.
&ldquo;It&hellip; it actually NICE,&rdquo; he say, genuinely surprised.
&ldquo;WHAT?!&rdquo;
&ldquo;De comb soft and chewy like&hellip; like&hellip; I don&rsquo;t even know what to compare it to! And de rest taste like regular chicken but more&hellip; more CHICKENY. But dat COMB, Wilar! De texture! It like chewing on a little piece of magic!&rdquo;
Wilar look like he was gon faint.
Speedeet grin and take another big scoop of de fried rice.
&ldquo;Wilar, you missing out. Dis is de best fried rice I ever eat in me life!&rdquo;
üèÉ DE AFTERMATH When dey finally leave de restaurant, Speedeet belly was FULL and he mind was BLOWN.
&ldquo;Wilar, you know what dis mean?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Dat you crazy?&rdquo;
&ldquo;No! It mean we been eating chicken WRONG dis whole time! We been throwing away de best parts!&rdquo;
Wilar shake he head. &ldquo;Speedeet, I not eating no chicken head. Not today. Not tomorrow. Not EVER.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Suit yourself.&rdquo; Speedeet pat he belly satisfied. &ldquo;More for me.&rdquo;
Dey walk back toward Pike Street, de afternoon sun warm on dey backs.
&ldquo;You know,&rdquo; Wilar say after a while, &ldquo;you really eat dat thing, eh?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yup.&rdquo;
&ldquo;De whole head?&rdquo;
&ldquo;De WHOLE head. Comb and all.&rdquo;
Wilar was quiet for a moment. Den he start to laugh.
&ldquo;Speedeet, you is really something else, you know dat?&rdquo;
Speedeet grin. &ldquo;Dat&rsquo;s why dey call me SPEEDEET, bai. First to try everything. Scared of NOTHING.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Except Miss Doreen.&rdquo;
&ldquo;&hellip;Except Miss Doreen. But dat woman have a BROOM.&rdquo;
üçö DE LESSON Dat night, Speedeet lay in he bed thinking about de day.
He had seen de inside of a real Chinese restaurant kitchen. He had taste dishes he never even know existed. He had eat a CHICKEN HEAD and live to tell de tale.
And dat comb? Dat soft, chewy, unusual comb? He was STILL thinking about de texture. How it bounce in he mouth. How different it was from anything else he ever eat.
Life was full of surprises, he realize. You never know what you gon find when you brave enough to try something new.
Even if dat something new got a little red comb on top.
He smile in de darkness.
Tomorrow, he would tell de whole Pike Street crew about he adventure. Little Sanjay wouldn&rsquo;t believe he. Keisha would say he lying. Ravi would probably dare he to do it again.
And he would.
Because dat&rsquo;s what Speedeet do.
He go first.
He try everything.
He eat de chicken head.
And he enjoy every bite.
THE END
Next time on Speedeet &amp; Wilar: De boys discover what REALLY in de black pudding at de market. Wilar might never eat again.
Speedeet &amp; Wilar are two 12-year-old best friends from Pike Street, Kitty, Georgetown. Speedeet is the brave one who jumps first. Wilar is the careful one who thinks twice. Together, they get into ‚Äî and out of ‚Äî all kinds of trouble. Their stories are written in authentic Guyanese Creolese.
üìö Want more adventures? The Speedeet &amp; Wilar book series is available on Amazon!

Welcome to the Rumor Mill - where we imagine what Georgetown might be whispering about if Georgetown whispered about completely fictional things. Any resemblance to real persons or events is coincidental and honestly impressive.
üí¨ OVERHEARD AT OASIS A certain well-dressed gentleman was spotted at Oasis Cafe explaining to his lunch companion why the garbage situation is &ldquo;actually a strategic opportunity for community engagement.&rdquo;
His companion reportedly asked: &ldquo;So when the garbage getting picked up?&rdquo;
The gentleman&rsquo;s response: &ldquo;You&rsquo;re missing the bigger picture.&rdquo;
The garbage, we&rsquo;re told, is still there.
üí¨ THE ROUNDABOUT CHRONICLES Commuters stuck at Eccles Roundabout have reportedly started a WhatsApp group called &ldquo;Roundabout Therapy.&rdquo;
Activities include:
Sharing audiobook recommendations for the 45-minute wait Rating which lane moves fastest (spoiler: none of them) Debating whether to just swim across the river instead One member allegedly suggested they should hold their own parliament sessions during peak hours since &ldquo;we have more time than the National Assembly anyway.&rdquo;
üí¨ POLITICAL MUSICAL CHAIRS Word on the street is that certain opposition figures have been practicing their &ldquo;congratulations&rdquo; speeches - the kind you give when you don&rsquo;t mean it.
Meanwhile, other opposition figures have allegedly been practicing their &ldquo;I told you so&rdquo; speeches for approximately six months from now.
Everyone, it seems, is rehearsing for a play nobody has finished writing.
üí¨ THE SOLAR PANEL SITUATION A Linden businessman reportedly told his wife: &ldquo;We getting solar panels!&rdquo;
His wife: &ldquo;Good, we saving money!&rdquo;
Him: &ldquo;No, the government building them.&rdquo;
His wife: &ldquo;So we saving money?&rdquo;
Him: &ldquo;Eventually. Maybe. The meeting say so.&rdquo;
His wife: &ldquo;So I should still pay GPL this month?&rdquo;
Him: &ldquo;&hellip;yes.&rdquo;
üí¨ COURTHOUSE FASHION WATCH Legal observers have noticed an uptick in expensive suits at the Georgetown courthouse.
&ldquo;When the lawyers dress better than the judges,&rdquo; one observer noted, &ldquo;you know the case is either very important or very expensive. Usually both.&rdquo;
Coffee sales at nearby shops have reportedly tripled. Extended hearings are good for business.
üí¨ THE MASH PREPARATION DRAMA A Georgetown mas camp is allegedly in crisis mode after their lead designer announced the theme would be &ldquo;Sustainable Fashion&rdquo; - meaning recycled materials only.
Band members are reportedly concerned that &ldquo;recycled&rdquo; might mean &ldquo;those same feathers from 2019.&rdquo;
The designer insists it&rsquo;s &ldquo;innovation.&rdquo;
The band members insist it&rsquo;s &ldquo;budget cuts with extra steps.&rdquo;
üí¨ DIPLOMATIC DINNER DISASTER A certain embassy reportedly held a dinner last week where the main course arrived late because - you guessed it - the delivery truck got stuck in Eccles traffic.
By the time the food arrived, the appetizers had been so thoroughly consumed that one diplomat allegedly asked if &ldquo;the bread basket counts as the main course in Guyanese culture.&rdquo;
It does not. But everyone was too polite to say so.
üí¨ THE GYM CONFESSION Overheard at a Georgetown gym, 6 AM:
Person 1: &ldquo;You hear about the Police Academy thing?&rdquo;
Person 2: &ldquo;Yeah, serious allegations.&rdquo;
Person 1: &ldquo;At least they investigating.&rdquo;
Person 2: &ldquo;True. Pass the weights.&rdquo;
Person 1: &ldquo;You think they&rsquo;ll actually find anything?&rdquo;
Person 2: &ldquo;Brother, I just trying to do my biceps. Save the politics for after coffee.&rdquo;
üí¨ VENDOR WISDOM A Stabroek Market vendor, when asked about the Opposition Leader situation:
&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t follow politics. I follow money. When somebody come to my stall, I don&rsquo;t ask who they vote for. I ask what they buying.&rdquo;
Pause
&ldquo;But if you ask me personally? All ah dem need to sit down and talk. This country too small for all this drama.&rdquo;
She then sold three pounds of tomatoes and moved on with her day.
The Rumor Mill is entirely fictional and meant for entertainment. We make up everything. Don&rsquo;t sue us.
Disclaimer: All characters and situations in this column are entirely fictional. Any resemblance to actual persons, living or dead, or actual events is purely coincidental. This is satire, not reporting.

Your 5-minute Guyanese news circus ‚Äî now with 100% less cash grants ‚òïüá¨üáæ
üí∏ CASH GRANTS: &ldquo;NOT SUSTAINABLE&rdquo; ‚Äî PRESIDENT What Happened: President Ali declared that future cash grants are &ldquo;not sustainable,&rdquo; warning that &ldquo;some people would use this as a political opportunity.&rdquo;
The Backstory: Just one year ago, the government was &ldquo;committed to making future cash grants.&rdquo; What a difference 365 days makes!
The Math:
2025: &ldquo;We are committed to future cash grants!&rdquo; 2026: &ldquo;Cash grants are not sustainable.&rdquo; Also 2026: Oil production approaching 1 million barrels per day. Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;When election coming, cash grant sustainable. When election done, cash grant unsustainable. Is like magic ‚Äî de money just disappear!&rdquo;
üóëÔ∏è GEORGETOWN: MINISTER SAYS &ldquo;UNACCEPTABLE,&rdquo; CITY HALL SAYS &ldquo;WE&rsquo;LL GET BACK TO YOU&rdquo; What Happened: Local Government Minister Priya Manickchand held an emergency virtual meeting with Mayor Alfred Mentore over the &ldquo;unacceptable&rdquo; state of Georgetown. The city was given until 11 AM Monday to present a cleanup plan.
The Quote: &ldquo;Sanitation services, solid waste disposal, garbage collection etc must be reliable, predictable and effective. Or they are wasting time.&rdquo;
Translation: Georgetown smells like a combination of stagnant drain water, burning garbage, and broken promises.
Current Status of Georgetown:
‚òê Clean ‚òê Habitable ‚òëÔ∏è A talking point for politicians Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;City Hall got till 11 AM to fix Georgetown. De garbage pile got till noon to laugh.&rdquo;
üë©‚Äçüè´ TEACHERS UNION: &ldquo;WE&rsquo;VE BEEN WRITING LETTERS, NOBODY ANSWERING&rdquo; What Happened: GTU President Coretta McDonald says the Education Ministry is delaying a crucial meeting on teacher promotions. Teachers haven&rsquo;t been promoted in three years, and many are retiring without the positions they deserved.
The Problem: The Teaching Service Commission was reconstituted without an Opposition Leader in place ‚Äî which the GTU says is &ldquo;a direct ploy by the government.&rdquo;
Ministry&rsquo;s Apparent Strategy:
Receive letter requesting meeting Look at letter Put letter in drawer Repeat McDonald&rsquo;s Assessment: &ldquo;The longer the ministry delays the meeting with the GTU, our teachers are going to be in jeopardy again.&rdquo;
Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;Teacher write letter to Ministry. Ministry write letter to TSC. TSC write letter to President. President write letter to 2027.&rdquo;
üè´ HINTERLAND SCHOOLS: &ldquo;FAR FROM OPERATIONAL READINESS&rdquo; ‚Äî OPPOSITION What Happened: Opposition MP Sherod Duncan visited two school construction sites in Region Nine ‚Äî the $215 million Nappi Secondary School and the $182 million Tabatinga Secondary School ‚Äî and reported concerns about progress.
Duncan&rsquo;s Finding: The schools are &ldquo;far from operational readiness.&rdquo;
Government&rsquo;s Likely Response: &ldquo;The projects are 90% complete and on track for completion soon.&rdquo;
The Eternal Guyanese Infrastructure Formula:
Announced: 100% enthusiasm Groundbreaking: 100% ribbon Completion: 90% (forever) ‚õΩ GAS-TO-ENERGY: CONTROL ROOMS ARRIVE AT WALES What Happened: Control rooms for the Gas-to-Energy project were transported to the Wales site on Saturday evening, marking &ldquo;another key milestone.&rdquo;
Translation: Big boxes arrived. Milestone achieved.
Project Status Update:
‚úÖ Boxes delivered ‚úÖ Photos taken ‚úÖ Press release issued ‚è≥ Actual gas flowing: End of 2026 (we think) Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;Control room reach Wales. Now we just need de gas, de pipes, de turbines, de transmission lines, and de prayers.&rdquo;
üè• HOSPITAL TRAGEDY: GPHC LAUNCHES INVESTIGATION What Happened: A 22-year-old pregnant woman died after jumping from the third-floor window of the female medical ward at Georgetown Public Hospital on Sunday evening. The hospital has launched an internal investigation.
The Questions: Family members are asking how a patient &ldquo;displaying clear psychological distress&rdquo; was able to leave her bed unaccompanied and access a window.
GPHC Statement: The hospital says a psychiatric evaluation was conducted and &ldquo;no psychotic symptoms or suicidal thoughts&rdquo; were identified.
If You Need Help: The Mental Health Unit&rsquo;s Suicide Prevention Hotline is 915. A mental health emergency is a real emergency.
üåä NEW PASSENGER VESSEL: &ldquo;SOON TO BE RENAMED&rdquo; What Happened: A 2024-built vessel arrived from Greece to serve Region One (Barima-Waini). The ship sailed 5,200 nautical miles across the Atlantic.
Highlights:
Fully air-conditioned Brand new seating Will &ldquo;shorten travel time significantly&rdquo; The Real Question: What will they name it?
Our Suggestions:
MV Slow But Sure MV We Reach When We Reach MV Better Than The Last One MV Sea Minibus üó≥Ô∏è OPPOSITION LEADER: STILL LOADING&hellip; What Happened: Letters to the editor are now asking the Speaker of the National Assembly to explain why he hasn&rsquo;t convened the meeting to elect an Opposition Leader ‚Äî over 3 months after elections.
Government&rsquo;s Position: &ldquo;We have no role in this.&rdquo;
Speaker&rsquo;s Position: [No comment available]
Constitutional Position: Article 184 says the Speaker must convene the meeting.
Actual Position: ü§∑
Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;Opposition Leader seat so empty, spider done build house inside.&rdquo;
üìä INFLATION: THE NUMBERS VS THE VIBES What Happened: A Stabroek News letter writer pointed out that official CPI data claims housing costs decreased by 1% since 2020.
The Official Numbers:
Housing: -1.0% Food: +50.7% Transportation: +3.3% The Reality: Try renting an apartment in Georgetown for 2020 prices. Go ahead. We&rsquo;ll wait.
Bonus: The New Guyana Marketing Corporation has stopped publishing market prices. No data, no problem!
Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;According to government, everything cheap. According to market, everything expensive. According to we pocket, nothing deh inside.&rdquo;
üèè SPORTS CORNER West Indies will warm up for the T20 World Cup with a three-match series against Afghanistan in Dubai. The World Cup starts February 7 in India and Sri Lanka.
Guyana Women&rsquo;s Cricket: Captain Shemaine Campbelle scored an unbeaten 50 as the defending champions beat Jamaica by 4 wickets in the CWI Women&rsquo;s Blaze T20 Championships.
‚òÄÔ∏è WEATHER Georgetown: Partly cloudy with scattered showers of government announcements. High of 31¬∞C. 90% chance of someone saying &ldquo;milestone.&rdquo;
üéØ FINAL SCORE Topic Government Says Reality Cash grants Not sustainable Oil revenue: very sustainable Georgetown Unacceptable Also unacceptable yesterday Teacher promotions We&rsquo;re working on it 3 years and counting Opposition Leader Not our problem Also not solved Inflation Under control Your grocery bill: LOL That&rsquo;s your Tuesday. Georgetown is dirty, teachers are waiting, cash grants are cancelled, and somewhere a control room is sitting in Wales wondering what it did to deserve this.
