Speedeet and Wilar were supposed to be watching the Women&rsquo;s T20 match on TV. Guyana versus Jamaica, and Captain Campbelle was batting.
But then Speedeet&rsquo;s phone buzzed.
&ldquo;Nani need me go clinic with she,&rdquo; Speedeet said, reading the message. &ldquo;Blood pressure check.&rdquo;
Wilar shrugged. &ldquo;Match almost done anyway. We winning.&rdquo;
They found Nani at the bus stop, clutching her patient card ‚Äî the worn folder that survived twenty years of clinic visits.
&ldquo;You boys coming? Good. Plenty confusion these days.&rdquo;
The polyclinic had TWO lines.
&ldquo;New system here! Old system there!&rdquo; the security guard shouted.
&ldquo;Register for what?&rdquo; Nani asked.
A woman turned around. &ldquo;Everything digital now. Computer system. But if you ain&rsquo;t register yet, you got to join the other line first.&rdquo;
Nani looked at her folder. &ldquo;I have this since 2006.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t matter. Everybody fresh.&rdquo;
Forty-five minutes later, they reached a desk with a brand-new laptop.
The young woman typed Nani&rsquo;s information, then opened the patient folder. She frowned at twenty years of handwritten notes, faded prescriptions, and coffee-stained test results.
&ldquo;I can only enter what I can read.&rdquo;
&ldquo;That say &lsquo;hypertension,&rsquo;&rdquo; Nani pointed. &ldquo;And that say &lsquo;reduce salt.&rsquo;&rdquo;
Fifteen minutes of squinting later: &ldquo;Okay, you&rsquo;re in the system. Take this number for the other line.&rdquo;
&ldquo;But I had 10 o&rsquo;clock appointment!&rdquo;
&ldquo;That was old system. Now you wait for the next available.&rdquo;
It was 11:30.
While Nani waited, the boys explored. Near the corner, an older man argued with a nurse.
&ldquo;What you mean you can&rsquo;t find my X-ray? I take it LAST MONTH!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Sir, it hasn&rsquo;t been migrated yet.&rdquo;
&ldquo;So I got to take ANOTHER one?&rdquo;
Speedeet whispered to Wilar: &ldquo;Progress messy, eh?&rdquo;
&ldquo;My father always say that.&rdquo;
At 1:15, Nani finally saw the doctor ‚Äî a young woman staring at a computer screen.
&ldquo;Mrs. Persaud? Let me pull up your file&hellip;&rdquo;
Type. Click. Frown. Type again.
&ldquo;It says you registered today?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Today for COMPUTER. But I coming here since 2006.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Do you have documentation?&rdquo;
Nani held up her folder triumphantly. &ldquo;EVERYTHING in here.&rdquo;
They went through her handwritten records together. Blood pressure: 138 over 85. Slightly elevated but stable. Same medication continued.
&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll enter this in the new system for next time.&rdquo;
