A Weekly Profile of Guyanese Excellence
At Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, Dr. Sharmila Persaud is performing some of the world&rsquo;s most complex brain surgeries. But every morning, she looks at a photo on her desk: her grandmother&rsquo;s wooden house in Berbice, where she grew up without electricity.
The Journey &ldquo;People ask me how I got from there to here,&rdquo; Dr. Persaud says, gesturing around her state-of-the-art operating suite. &ldquo;I tell them: I got here because I started there.&rdquo;
Born in New Amsterdam in 1985, Sharmila was the first in her family to attend university. Her father drove a taxi. Her mother sold vegetables at the market. They had one dream: their daughter would become a doctor.
Against the Odds The path wasn&rsquo;t easy:
Studied by kerosene lamp when power was out (which was often) Walked 3 miles to school in Berbice rain Helped her mother at the market before classes Won a scholarship to Queen&rsquo;s College in Georgetown Graduated top of her class at University of Guyana medical school A scholarship to Johns Hopkins came next. Then residency. Then fellowship. Now, at 40, she&rsquo;s one of the leading neurosurgeons in North America.
The Guyana Connection But success hasn&rsquo;t severed her roots√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùit&rsquo;s strengthened them.
Dr. Persaud:
Returns to Guyana quarterly for medical missions Has trained 15 Guyanese doctors in neurosurgery techniques Established a scholarship fund for Berbice students Donated equipment to Georgetown Public Hospital Mentors young Guyanese doctors remotely &ldquo;I&rsquo;m successful because Guyana made me who I am,&rdquo; she explains. &ldquo;The work ethic, the resilience, the determination√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùthat&rsquo;s all Guyana.&rdquo;
The Berbice Spirit She tells the story of performing a 14-hour surgery on a young patient last year. Exhausted, she almost asked her team to take over.
&ldquo;Then I remembered my mother standing in the market for 16 hours a day, never complaining. I thought: if she could do that selling vegetables, I can do this saving a life.&rdquo;
The surgery succeeded.
Advice for Young Guyanese Dr. Persaud is often asked to speak at schools in Guyana. Her message is consistent:
&ldquo;Your circumstances don&rsquo;t define your destination. I studied by lamplight. You have electricity and internet. You have no excuse√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùand unlimited potential.&rdquo;
She pauses. &ldquo;But also: never forget where you came from. Success means nothing if you don&rsquo;t bring others along.&rdquo;
The Return Plan Dr. Persaud has a five-year plan: establish Guyana&rsquo;s first dedicated neurosurgery center in Georgetown.
&ldquo;We train excellent doctors in Guyana,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;But then we lose them because we don&rsquo;t have the facilities to use their skills. That has to change.&rdquo;
She&rsquo;s already raised $2 million toward the project. The Guyanese diaspora is contributing. So are international partners impressed by Guyana&rsquo;s potential.
&ldquo;My grandmother&rsquo;s generation left Guyana for opportunity,&rdquo; Dr. Persaud reflects. &ldquo;My generation left Guyana for education. The next generation? They should stay in Guyana for both.&rdquo;
Beyond Medicine Outside the hospital, Dr. Persaud maintains her Guyanese identity fiercely:
Cooks pepperpot for colleagues every Christmas Teaches her children Creolese phrases Wears her Guyana flag pin on her white coat Serves on the board of the Baltimore Guyanese Association &ldquo;I&rsquo;m Guyanese first,&rdquo; she says simply. &ldquo;Everything else is just what I do, not who I am.&rdquo;
The Photo That photo on her desk√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùthe one of her grandmother&rsquo;s house in Berbice?
&ldquo;It reminds me every day why I do this work,&rdquo; she explains. &ldquo;And reminds me that no matter how far I&rsquo;ve come, that&rsquo;s still home.&rdquo;
Dr. Sharmila Persaud proves what&rsquo;s possible when Guyanese excellence meets opportunity. And more importantly, she&rsquo;s ensuring the next generation won&rsquo;t have to leave Guyana to reach it.
